\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b The Inkwell Hour\b0\par
\i A short test story for PawPoller QA.\i0\par
By Test Author.\par
\par
The clock above the desk was a quarter of an hour fast, which Adler had stopped resetting because he liked the small lie of it. It made the day feel a little longer than it was. He poured the ink and watched it bead up on the surface of the paper before it sank in, the way good ink does on bad paper.\par
\par
He wrote three lines. Then he stopped. Then he wrote three more.\par
\par
The lamp guttered once around midnight, took itself seriously again, and burned steady until dawn. By then he had filled the sheet, both sides, in handwriting so small that he himself would not be able to read it back the next morning.\par
\par
That, of course, had been the point.\par
\par
\i End of The Inkwell Hour.\i0\par
